<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>Any method is limited in its inventor's knowledge and understandings of problems.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>This paper attempts to explore the problem of summarization from multiple dimensions (especially from empiricism, rationalism, evolutionism, and social/individual constructionism) so as to form a general summarization methodology.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>Each dimension consists of some specific methods.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>Integrating different methods is a way to break the limitations.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>Various methods can be organized in a multi-dimensional methodological space as shown in Figure 2.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>Rational study derives new theories and methods according to existing theories, methods and phenomena.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>Coordinating different dimensions is a way to generate new methods.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>Different dimensions regulate different classes of method.</a>
